<tt>Sun Apr 13 11:47:59 US/Eastern 1997
</tt><p>
I served stateside from 1965 to 1968, trained at Ft Sam as a neurospsychiatric medic. At Letterman and later at Tripler waves of military and dependent staff came through our wards.<br>
My thoughts about the war were confused at the time, but my thoughts about the men and women suffering trauma that would like last a lifetime were not confused. Nor are they today.<br>
Several memories stand out: More than a few infantry personnel arrived at Triple after the tranquilizers they were given proved ineffective in a combat setting. Marines on Thorazine. <br>
On another occasion a  young soldier from Philadelphia arrived mute, in a catatonic state unable to retell, until weeks of hospitalization, the chase through the jungle that left his squad dead or captured and caused him to commit desparate acts to survive. <br>
Where is he now? How is he now.<br>
The most bizarre memory is of a Navy navigator who had been assigned to surviellance duty over China/Vietnam to snoop and gain intelligence data.  While on R&amp;R in Hawaii he found himself at the officer's club in Waikiki...having a few drinks, one of which at least was accompanied with LSD. Knowingly or unknowingly.<br>
Naked and quite high we took him with SP assistance back to hospital, where within a day or so things seemed normal. Shipped back to Oak Knoll he received a clean bill of health and dropped in a month later to say he was going back to duty. Flying over SE Asia. <br><br>
Am interested in hearing from vets or medics about the topic.<br><br>

